fields.name: Bogs, Marshes, Swamps, Fens, Peatlands [generally over 8 ha]
Permanent Saline, Brackish or Alkaline Lakes
Karst and Other Subterranean Inland Aquatic Systems
Arthroleptis stenodactylus
fields.notes: Arthroleptis lonnbergi was removed from the synonymy of Arthroleptis stenodactylus by Pickersgill (2007). However, the species was synonymized again under Arthroleptis stenodactylus by Blackburn (2010 in Frost 2013). Current systematic work is expected to result in recognizing some populations currently assigned to Arthroleptis stenodactylus as two or more distinct species (D. Blackburn pers. comm. October 2015).

fields.name: Vandijkophrynus gariepensis
fields.notes: Some isolated populations in the north of its range could be separate taxa.

fields.name: Amietophrynus garmani
fields.notes: There is confusion regarding the taxonomy of this species and Amietophrynus poweri (M. Largen, J. Poynton, L. Mazibuko and M. Tandy pers. comm.). It is possible that the true Amietophrynus garmani is restricted to northeastern Africa, with animals from further south belonging to another species (Largen 2001). In this account, we follow the traditional understanding of the species' distribution and taxonomy, pending further information.

fields.name: Amietophrynus poweri
fields.notes: There is confusion regarding the taxonomy of this species and Amietophrynus garmani (M. Largen, J. Poynton, L. Mazibuko and M. Tandy pers. comm.)

fields.name: Heleophryne orientalis
fields.notes: It is not clear that this species is distinct from Heleophryne purcelli (L. Minter pers. comm.).

fields.name: Heleophryne purcelli
fields.notes: This species might include Heleophryne orientalis (L. Minter pers. comm.).

fields.name: Hemisus guineensis
fields.notes: This form is a complex of more than one species, probably comprising several species (M.-O. RÃ¶del pers comm.). In many parts of its range, the distinction between this species and Hemisus marmoratus is not clear. Ongoing taxonomic work (by de SÃ¡ and colleagues) will result in reshaping our knowledge of cryptic species richness and distributions of populations currently assigned to Hemisus marmoratus and H. guineensis.

fields.name: Hemisus marmoratus
fields.notes: It is possible that the subspecies Hemisus marmoratus sudanensis constitutes a separate species (RÃ¶del 2000). This species is probably a complex comprising several species (M.-O. RÃ¶del pers. comm.). Ongoing taxonomic work (by de SÃ¡ and colleagues) will result in reshaping our knowledge of cryptic diversity and distributions of populations currently assigned to Hemisus marmoratus and Hemisus guineensis. In several parts of its range, this species is not readily distinguishable from Hemisus guineensis.

fields.name: Afrixalus fornasini
fields.notes: Pickersgill (1996, 2007) recognized Afrixalus unicolor (Boettger, 1913) as a distinct species; thus Afrixalus fornasinii from South Africa to southern Tanzania (including the area around Lake Malawi) and A. unicolor from southern Tanzania (including Zanzibar and Pemba Islands) to Kenya. However, here we follow SchiÃ¸tz (1999) in considering these to constitute a single species.

fields.name: Hyperolius marmoratus
fields.notes: This species is part of the Hyperolius viridiflavus superspecies (Laurent 1983, SchiÃ¸tz 1971, 1999). It is considered here as a separate species following Wieczorek et al. (2000, 2001). It should be noted that the taxonomic relationships within this superspecies are still far from settled. Members of this superspecies, which consists of a large number of forms that are distributed, generally allopatrically, throughout the tropical African savanna, have a common morphology, voice and ecology, but with widely differing dorsal patterns. Laurent (1983) concluded that the concept of one species best expressed present knowledge, and A. SchiÃ¸tz (pers. comm.) agrees with this. Wieczorek et al. (2001) carried out an analysis based on mtDNA, and separated the forms that they examined into 10 species. However, they examined only 22 out of 45 recognized "subspecies". The following distinct forms were not treated in the analysis by Wieczorek et al. (2001) and therefore cannot be allocated to any their ten species: spatzi, pallidus, pachydermus, destefanii, variabilis, coerulescens, karissimbiensis, francoisi, sheldricki, rubripes, mwanzae, reesi, bitaeniatus, rhodoscelis, nyassae, taeniatus, insignis, alborufus, epheboides, aposematicus and broadleyi. An un-named form from Marsabit in northern Kenya also cannot be allocated within the Wieczorek et al. (2001) arrangement of species. The arrangement currently followed by the Global Amphibian Assessment is provisional, pending a more complete analysis of the relationships within the Hyperolius viridiflavus superspecies. A. SchiÃ¸tz (pers. comm.) considers that it would have been prefereable for the Global Amphibian Assessment to treat the Hyperolius viridiflavus superspecies as a single species, because under this arrangement, all the described forms are covered unambiguously. Pickersgill (2007) described Hyperolius fumatus as a new species, but we follow Frost (2007) Amphibian Species of the World 5.1 http://research.amnh.org/herpetology/amphibia/index.php in treating it as a synonym of H. marmoratus. Similarly, Pickersgill (2007) treated verrucosus, taeniatus, aposematicus, alborufus, and nyassae as separate species, but we follow Frost (2007) in including them under H. marmoratus.

fields.name: Breviceps adspersus
fields.notes: This species hybridises in places with Breviceps mossambicus, leading to confusion about its distributional limits (Poynton and Broadley 1985). Breviceps adspersus pentheri in the Eastern Cape might be a distinct species L. Minter pers. comm.).

fields.name: Breviceps mossambicus
fields.notes: This species hybridises in places with Breviceps adspersus, leading to confusion about its distributional limits (Poynton and Broadley 1985). Some specimens previously referred to B. mossambicus have recently been separated to a new species, B. fichus (Channing and Minter, 2004).

fields.name: Cacosternum boettgeri
fields.notes: This form consists of many cryptic species. We follow Channing et al. (2005) in removing Kenyan and Tanzanian population from this species, under the name Cacosternum plimptoni. Ethiopian populations should presumably also be separated as a distinct species, but for now we treat them as part of C. boettgeri.

fields.name: Cacosternum nanum
fields.notes: We follow Scott (in press) in considering the subspecies, Cacosternum nanum parvum, as a distinct species. Specimens from north-eastern Kwa-Zulu Natal have been found which have a different call, and might represent another undescribed species (E. Scott, unpublished data).

fields.name: Cacosternum parvum
fields.notes: We follow Scott (in press) in considering Cacosternum parvum as a species distinct from C. nanum.

fields.name: Cacosternum platys
fields.notes: This species was removed from the synonymy of Cacosternum boettgeri by Channing (2001), where it had been placed by Poynton (1964). Channing et al. (2013) described four new species in Cacosternum genus and revised the distribution of known Cacosternum species, so the range of C. platys has been restricted (southern Cape Peninsula populations are now referred to as C. australis, sister species of C. platys).

fields.name: Phrynobatrachus mababiensis
fields.notes: The taxonomic status of this species in relation to Phrynobatrachus parvulus and P. ukingensis requires clarification (Poynton and Broadley 1985b). It is likely to represent more than one species based on molecular evidence (S. Loader pers. comm. Nov 2012). Zimkus et al. (2010) noted that nominal Phrynobatrachus mababiensis covers two distantly related species.

fields.name: Phrynobatrachus natalensis
fields.notes: This form almost certainly consists of a number of cryptic species (RÃ¶del 2000).

fields.name: Xenopus muelleri
fields.notes: This species is possibly composed of two species, a west African form and an east-southern African form (R.C. Tinsley pers. comm.). It is part of a complex of poorly understood species closely related to Xenopus laevis.  It seems likely that many records from the inland parts of Tanzania currently assigned to this species should in fact be referred toXenopus borealis, and the distribution maps probably records this species as occurring much too widely in this country.

fields.name: Amietia fuscigula
fields.notes: A study by Channing and Baptista (2013) based on mitochondrial DNA, advertisement calls and morphology splits this form into two distantly related taxa, which were previously assessed together: Amietia fuscigula (DumÃ©ril & Bibron 1841) from the south-western Cape and a recently described species, Amietia poyntoni.

fields.name: Ptychadena oxyrhynchus
fields.notes: The status of Phrynobatrachus hailiensis Meek and Eliot, 1897 from northern Somalia remains obscure. It is usually considered to be a synonym of this species, but its type locality falls far outside the otherwise known range of Ptychadena oxyrhynchus, and so it is not included here, pending further investigation of its status.

fields.name: Ptychadena taenioscelis
fields.notes: We treat this as a species distinct from Ptychadena pumilio, following Poynton and Broadley (1985).

fields.name: Strongylopus bonaespei
fields.notes: Earlier literature refers to this species as Rana fasciata montana.

fields.name: Amietia hymenopus
fields.notes: Until 2008 the Maluti River Frog was referred to Amietia vertebralis and the Phofung River Frog to Strongylopus hymenopus; a recent revision of type specimens has clarified the confusion between the two species, showing that Amietia vertebralis is widespread in Lesotho, KwaZulu-Natal and the Eastern Cape Province in South Africa, while Amietia hymenopus occurs within a more restricted range range in north-eastern Lesotho and the Drakensberg highlands (Channing 2015).

fields.name: Tomopterna cryptotis
fields.notes: Tomopterna kachowskii and T. elegans have been removed from synonymy with this species (Zimkus and Larson 2011). This species still requires taxonomic research to understand its full distribution and status, particularly subpopulations in Zaire (Zimkus and Larson 2011).

fields.name: Tomopterna tandyi
fields.notes: This species is a tetraploid species species that is very similar to, and easily confused with, Tomopterna cryptotis, T. delalandii and T. damarensis (Channing and Bogart 1996; Dawood and Channing 2002).

fields.name: Leptopelis xenodactylus
fields.notes: The relationships between this and other species without toe discs requires a detailed taxonomic study using molecular and morphological methodologies.

fields.name: Microbatrachella capensis
fields.notes: A question hangs over the taxonomic significance of disjunct populations of this species.

fields.name: Xenopus gilli
fields.notes: A deep genetic split characterises the disjunct distribution of this species.

fields.name: Breviceps gibbosus
fields.notes: This species, originally named Rana gibbosa, was the first African frog species to be entered into the Linnean system of nomenclature in 1758.

fields.name: Cacosternum poyntoni
fields.notes: This species is apparently an aberrant melanistic colour form of Cacosternum nanum (Scott in press).

fields.name: Capensibufo rosei
fields.notes: Phylogenetic analysis of this genus showed the presence of multiple lineages in what had originally been attributed to two species (Capensibufo rosei and C. tradouwi). Within C. rosei, at least 5 distinct lineages are present, such that Capensibufo rosei on the Cape Peninsula is now recognised as the only member of this taxon, with others being Capensibufo xx and xx (Tolley et al. 2010, Cressey et al. 2013, Channing et al. 20xx).

fields.name: Amietia vertebralis
fields.notes: This species has a confusing taxonomic history which has been reviewed several times (Tarrant et al. 2008, Channing 2015). Most recently known as Amietia umbraculata, Channing (2015) reverted the name to A. vertebralis based on examination of type specimens and Zoological Nomenclature rules.

fields.name: Amietophrynus pantherinus
fields.notes: Reports of this species occurring between Agulhas and Wilderness, the westernmost record of Sclerophrys pardalis (Minter et al. 2004) remain unconfirmed.

fields.name: Afrixalus spinifrons
fields.notes: Afrixalus spinifrons is an endemic species complex comprising Afrixalus knysnae and two subspecies, Afrixalus spinifrons spinifrons confined to the central KwaZulu-Natal coast and A. s. intermedius from the KwaZulu-Natal midlands (sensu Pickersgill 1996). Subpopulations from the Eastern Cape and KwaZulu-Natal previously assigned to Afrixalus knysnae were re-assigned to A. spinifrons (Pickersgill 1996). Tarrant (2012) showed that, according to molecular and morphological descriptions, Eastern Cape populations should be referred to A. s. intermedius instead of A. s. spinifrons as previously thought. Tarrant (2012) also suggested that the uMkomaas River is a possible boundary to A. s. spinifrons. The two subspecies are distinguishable on the basis of morphology, genetics and calls.

fields.name: Afrixalus knysnae
fields.notes: This species is closely related to Afrixalus spinifrons (Cope 1862). Species boundaries in this complex are uncertain and taxonomic studies using calls, morphology and genetics are necessary.

fields.name: Breviceps sylvestris
fields.notes: There are questions regarding the validity of two subspecies: Breviceps sylvestris sylvestris and B. s. taeniatus.

fields.name: Arthroleptella landdrosia
fields.notes: The taxonomy of A. landdrosia is under revision and is presently best considered complex. The current assessment will be an evaluation of the entire complex.

fields.name: Anhydrophryne ngongoniensis
fields.notes: This species was recently found to belong in the genus Anhydrophryne rather than Arthroleptella (Dawood and Stam 2006).

fields.name: Xenopus laevis
fields.notes: Channing and Howell (2006) and Pickersgill (2007) treated the East African X.l. victorianus as a species in its own right, and we follow that arrangement. However, this leaves the odd situation of X. laevis being a southern African species, but with an isolated subspecies, X.l. sudanensis, in north-central Africa (which probably also needs to be recognized as a full species). Populations of X. laevis from the Cape of South Africa are genetically differentiated from populations elsewhere across Africa.

fields.name: Poyntonia paludicola
fields.notes: There is some evidence that disjunct populations may contain cryptic species.

fields.name: Heleophryne hewitti
fields.notes: The taxonomy of this genus is in need of revision.

fields.name: Amietia vandijki
fields.notes: The taxonomy of this genus and disjunct distributions of this species require attention.

fields.name: Cacosternum striatum
fields.notes: This species was resurrected from the synonymy of Cacosternum boettgeri by Lambiris (1988), where it had been placed by Poynton (1964).

fields.name: Ptychadena mascareniensis
fields.notes: This very widely distributed species is a complex of several species. A phylogeographic study by Vences et al. (2004) suggests that the populations of this species on the Seychelles and the Mascarene islands were introduced from Madagascar. However, the animals on Madagascar appear to have arrived on that island prior to its colonization by humans. Pickersgill (2007) treated Ptychadena hylaea as a separate species, but here we retain it within P. mascareniensis pending a more comprehensive resolution of this species complex. Records from Rwanda, Uganda, Kenya and Egypt were assigned to P. nilotica by Dehling and Sinsch (2013).

fields.name: Hyperolius acuticeps
fields.notes: There has been considerable debate on the taxonomic status of this species and others in the Hyperolius nasutus complex. Here we follow Channing, Moyer and Burger (2002) in considering Hyperolius acuticeps to be distinct from H. nasutus. However, we also follow Amiet (2005) in assigning West and Central African populations to H. adspersus and H. igbettensis, and Channing et al. (2013) in restricting H. acuticeps to Tanzania and Malawi, assigning the South African part of its range to H. poweri.

fields.name: Hyperolius poweri
fields.notes: Pickersgill (2007) removed this species from the synonymy of Hyperolius acuticeps based on its voice. It is a member of the H. nasutus complex, the taxonomy of which remains poorly known, so the validity of this species, like that of many other species in the complex, requires further clarification.

fields.name: Pyxicephalus edulis
fields.notes: This is a restricted concept of P. edulis following the split of the broader concept into this and P. angusticeps (Scott et al. 2013).

fields.name: Hemicordulia africana
fields.notes: Regarded as Hemicordulia asiatica Selys, 1878 but according to Dijkstra (pers. comm.) this is a separate species. There are major taxonomic uncertainties around this taxon.

fields.name: Pseudagrion draconis
fields.notes: A-group. Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B".

fields.name: Diplacodes luminans
fields.notes: Philonomon luminans is junior synonym to Diplacodes luminans (Dijkstra 2006).

fields.name: Pseudagrion newtoni
fields.notes:
A-group. Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B".

The earlier Cape records (Pinhey 1984) are doubtful and are probably Pseudagrion hageni hageni (Samways 2006).

fields.name: Aciagrion gracile
fields.notes: Western Africa records of this and the similar A. hamoni must be reviewed.

fields.name: Africallagma sinuatum
fields.notes: A. malawi specimen, described as Africallagma sinuatum f. fugax (Pinhey, 1962), differs significantly from A. sinuatum (Ris, 1921) and is expected to become a good species (May and Dijkstra in prep.).

fields.name: Gomphidia quarrei
fields.notes: Gomphidia balii Fraser, 1949 is possibly a synonym.

fields.name: Anax ephippiger
fields.notes: This species, formerly included in the genus Hemianax, is increasingly included in the genus Anax. As no genetic investigation is available, this remains controversial.

fields.name: Hemistigma albipunctum
fields.notes: The name is often misspelt as H. albipuncta.

fields.name: Azuragrion nigridorsum
fields.notes: This species potentially requires further investigation as there are discontinuities in habitat and behaviour across its range.

fields.name: Brachythemis leucosticta
fields.notes: The former Brachythemis leucosticta (Burmeister, 1839) was split in two distinct cryptic species (Dijkstra and Matushkina 2009), with B. impartita (Karsch, 1890) occurring from the south of Europe and northern Africa to central Africa, and the true B. leucosticta from the Sahel to South Africa. Both species overlap over a large part of central Africa.

fields.name: Ceriagrion suave
fields.notes: Ceriagrion moorei and C. hamoni may be synonymous with C. suave (Dijkstra 2005) and are treated as such here.

fields.name: Crocothemis sanguinolenta
fields.notes: Crocothemis sanguinolenta was first recorded from the Dead Sea by Morton (1924), based on three males in Ris' collection. Based on these specimens and new records, Schneider (1982) described the subspecies arabica. With more material at hand Dijkstra and Dingemanse (2000) found out that characters used to separate Levantine subpopulations fall within the variation of the nominal (African) form and concluded that arabica is not a valid subspecies.

fields.name: Diplacodes lefebvrii
fields.notes: The species name is often misspelt as Diplacodes lefebvrei.

fields.name: Gynacantha usambarica
fields.notes: Gynacantha zuluensis (Balinsky, 1961) is a synonym of Gynacantha usambarica  SjÃ¶stedt, 1909 (Djikstra 2005).

fields.name: Orthetrum stemmale
fields.notes: This species is seriously confused with O. brachiale.

fields.name: Lestes ictericus
fields.notes: This species has been confused in the past with L. ochraceus and L. pallidus (Gambles 1976) and records must be revised carefully.

fields.name: Orthetrum trinacria
fields.notes: Subpopulations from Iraq and Kuwait have been ascribed to a poorly defined subspecies, Orthetrum trinacria igarashii Asahina, 1973. Its taxonomic status needs clarification.

fields.name: Lestes pallidus
fields.notes: This species has been confused in the past with Lestes ochraceus and L. ictericus (Gambles 1976) and records must be revised carefully.

fields.name: Lestinogomphus angustus
fields.notes: This species is often mixed up with L. africanus, of which the systematic status remains unclear.

fields.name: Phyllogomphus selysi
fields.notes: Phyllogomphus orientalis Fraser, 1957 is a possible synonym.

fields.name: Notiothemis jonesi
fields.notes: The paler subspecies N. auricolor occurs in Uganda.

fields.name: Zygonoides fuelleborni
fields.notes: This genus has been object of taxonomic changes: Olpogastra fuelleborni is junior synonym to Zygonoides fuelleborni (Dijkstra et al. 2006).

fields.name: Orthetrum brachiale
fields.notes: This species is seriously confused with O. stemmale.

fields.name: Orthetrum caffrum
fields.notes: In Africa it is often confused with Orthetrum camerunense.

fields.name: Orthetrum julia
fields.notes: The paler subspecies falsum occurs in East Africa and parts of Southern Africa.

fields.name: Palpopleura lucia
fields.notes: Palpopleura portia, often considered a form of P. lucia, was proven to be a good species (Mitchell and Samways 2005).

fields.name: Palpopleura portia
fields.notes: Palpopleura portia, often considered a form or subspecies of P. lucia, was proven to be a good species (Mitchell and Samways 2005).

fields.name: Paragomphus cognatus
fields.notes: A dark form, P. nguelicus, occurs in southern Africa. The taxonomy of the cognatus group of Paragomphus is unresolved and in urgent need of a throughout revision.

fields.name: Paragomphus genei
fields.notes: Melanic insular subpopulations from the Anjouan island have been described as a distinct subspecies, Paragomphus genei ndzuaniensis Levasseur, 2007. As similar subpopulations are known in mainland Africa, more genetic research should be done before validating such subspecific division, which was done based on very weak criteria and without taking the variability of other subpopulations into account.

fields.name: Trithemis kirbyi
fields.notes: The former splitting into a nominotypical form and a subspecies Trithemis kirbyi ardens (GerstÃ¤cker, 1891) is currently challenged because of different opinions on biogeographic interpretation in the distribution of phenotypes.

fields.name: Platycypha caligata
fields.notes: A specimen from the shores of Lake Malawi may be a new species.

fields.name: Zygonyx torridus
fields.notes:
It is still often misspelt as Zygonyx torrida, from its former name, Pseudomacromia torrida.

Specimens from Mauritius have been described as a distinct subspecies, Zygonyx torridus insulanus (sub Z. torrida insulana) by Pinhey (1981), based on their smaller size and the occurrence of a yellow tinge on all wings in three males only. However, Jacquemin and Boudot (1999) specified that two males from Mauritius and a third from La RÃ©union islands agree perfectly in size and wing colour (fully hyaline) with the nominotypical subspecies. Similarly, specimens from India, which have been doubtfully ascribed to a distinct subspecies, Zygonyx torridus isis (sub Zygonyx isis, then Z. torrida isis) by Fraser (1924, 1926) on the basis of their faint yellow suffused wings in six males and without any comparison with the African subpopulations. This poorly defined taxon is in need of re-evaluation. Here Z. t. isis is tentatively treated as a synonym of Z. t. torridus.

fields.name: Pseudagrion acaciae
fields.notes: Former records of Kenya correspond to P. niloticum. Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B". This species belongs to group B.

fields.name: Pseudagrion assegaii
fields.notes: Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B". P. assegaii is a B-group species.

fields.name: Pseudagrion coelestis
fields.notes: Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B". Pseudagrion coelestis is a B-group species.

fields.name: Pseudagrion commoniae
fields.notes: Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B". This species belongs to group B.

fields.name: Pseudagrion gamblesi
fields.notes: Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B". This species is part of group A.

fields.name: Pseudagrion hageni
fields.notes: Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B". This species is part of group B.

fields.name: Pseudagrion hamoni
fields.notes: This widely distributed and abundant species is often misidentified and confused with similar taxa.

fields.name: Pseudagrion massaicum
fields.notes: Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B". This species is part of group B.

fields.name: Pseudagrion salisburyense
fields.notes: Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B". This species is part of group A.

fields.name: Pseudagrion sjoestedti
fields.notes: The status of numerous described subspecies in this variable species requires reassessment. Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B". Pseudagrion sjoetedti is a B group species.

fields.name: Pseudagrion spernatum
fields.notes: Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B". This species belongs to group A.

fields.name: Pseudagrion sublacteum
fields.notes:
The small dark form, rusingae, occurs on the northern shores and islands of Lake Victoria.

Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B". This species belongs to group B.

fields.name: Pseudagrion sudanicum
fields.notes: Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B". Pseudagrion sudanicum is a B group species.

fields.name: Rhyothemis semihyalina
fields.notes:
The nominotypical subspecies is restricted to Mauritius Islands and is defined by small dark patches at the base of the forewings and the dark area of the hindwings reaching the nodus. The subspecies Rhyothemis semihyalina separata (Selys, 1849) extends over the whole continental African and Arabian range of the species and is defined by forewings lacking dark patches at base (totally hyaline) and the dark area of the hindwings not reaching the nodus.

Another subspecies, R. s. syriaca (Selys, 1849) was described from the Jordan Valley, where it was supposedly endemic (and is now extinct), and was defined by a dark area at the base of hindwings which do not reach the nodus and where the last row of cells on the posterior wing margin remains hyaline.

Such criteria used for subspecific separation are very weak and lack of true statistical basis, and there is some evidences that individuals from Gabon, Namibia and Madagascar may show a dark patch at the base of forewings and a dark area in hindwings reaching or not the nodus (i.e. <http://www.africa-dragonfly.net/pics/a488/P1010356.jpg>, Pinhey 1962, Suhling and Martens 2007). That suggests a stronger intraspecific variability than initially expected. 

Therefore, most researchers do not retain this subspecific splitting, which is unlikely in such nomadic species, and further genetic study throughout this species range is needed.

fields.name: Tramea basilaris
fields.notes: This species is sometimes placed in Trapezostigma, which is a synonym of Tramea.

fields.name: Tramea limbata
fields.notes: This species is sometimes placed in Trapezostigma, which should be treated as a synonym of Tramea (Dijkstra et al. 2005).

fields.name: Trithemis annulata
fields.notes: Libellula haematina Rambur, 1842, described from Senegal and Madagascar, and claimed to be occurring in La RÃ©union, Mauritius and Sicily, represents the infraspecific variability and cannot be accepted as a valid taxon despite the treatment published by Ris (1912).

fields.name: Trithemis donaldsoni
fields.notes: The records of Trithemis donaldsoni from western Africa and Yemen have been recently ascribed to T. dejouxi Pinhey, 1978 (Dijkstra 2007), which is its sister species (Dijkstra et al. 2010). Both species may be easily confounded and their respective range is still unclear and needs further studies.

fields.name: Trithemis furva
fields.notes: The occurrence of Trithemis furva in west Africa is uncertain due to possible confusion with T. pruinata, which appears commoner in the west but rarer in the east and south Africa.

fields.name: Trithemis stictica
fields.notes: Subpopulations in the northern Kalahari basin that have been formerly identified as T. stictica are now known as a separate species.

fields.name: Urothemis edwardsii
fields.notes: The subspecies Urothemis edwardsii hulae Dumont, 1975, described from the upper Jordan Valley, falls within the variation range of the African and Arabian subpopulations (Samraoui et al. 1993) and is no longer recognized as valid.

fields.name: Pseudagrion inopinatum
fields.notes: Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B". P. inopinatum is an A-group species.

fields.name: Pseudagrion vaalense
fields.notes: B-group. Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B".

fields.name: Agriocnemis ruberrima
fields.notes: Two subspecies: ruberrima Balinsky, 1961 and albifrons Balinsky, 1961. Further taxonomic work is required as A. ruberrima may be split into two separate species.

fields.name: Pseudagrion citricola
fields.notes: A-group. Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B".

fields.name: Pseudagrion caffrum
fields.notes: A-group. Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B".

fields.name: Pseudagrion furcigerum
fields.notes: A-group. Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B".

fields.name: Pinheyschna subpupillata
fields.notes: Aeschna subpupillata is now placed in the genus Pinheyschna (Peters and Theischinger 2011).

fields.name: Pseudagrion makabusiense
fields.notes: Pseudagrion is likely to be split into two genera at some point. Until this taxonomic split occurs, the candidates for these two groups are highlighted by "group A" and "group B". P. makabusiense is an A-group species. The taxonomy of the species is likely to requires reform.

fields.name: Circus ranivorus
fields.notes: Permanent wetlands are required for breeding, feeding and roosting (van der Merwe 1981; Steyn 1982; Tarboton and Allan 1984; ASAB1:236-237). Nests are built in reeds over water (Barnes 2000) whilst small wetlands are used for foraging (Brown et al. 1982) and large wetlands for breeding (Barnes 2000).

fields.name: Podica senegalensis
fields.notes: Occurs in habitats <1500m above sea level (altitude). Avoids both stagnant water and fast-flowing waters, preferring clear, perennial rivers and streams lined with reeds and overhanging trees and shrubs (Barnes, 2000).

fields.name: Spheniscus demersus
fields.notes: The African Penguin breeds at 24 islands and three mainland sites between Hollamsbird Island off Namibia and Bird Island, Algoa Bay, South Africa. Altitude: Sea level.

fields.name: Rynchops flavirostris
fields.notes: Occurs on major tropical rivers and lakes.

fields.name: Gypaetus barbatus
fields.notes: It is a solitary, cliff-nesting species; it breeds above 1800 m a.s.l. although most nests are found in basalt rock formations above 2100 m a.s.l. (ASAB1: 154-155).

fields.name: Botaurus stellaris
fields.notes: Often patchy distribution in the warmer boreal and warm temperate zones from western Europe thorugh central Russia to the Pacific (Hagemeijer & Blair 1997). Altitude: 0-1750+m a.s.l.

fields.name: Turnix nanus
fields.notes: Grassland and savanna, mainly in moist woodland belts. Altitude: <1800 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Anthropoides paradiseus
fields.notes: Dry short grasslands, uses wetlands for breeding. In the arid Karro, the species occurs where perennial grasslands dominate the typical Karoo scrub. In the Fynbos it is restricted, almost exclusively, to intensively cultivated habitats. Altitude <2000 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Hirundo atrocaerulea
fields.notes: Altitude: 850-1900 m a.s.l. Restricted to small, fragmented sour grassland patches in the highlands of the eastern escaprment (ASAB2: 52-53).

fields.name: Spizocorys fringillaris
fields.notes: Localised within upland grassland, mostly coincident with black clay soils and Moist Clay Highveld Grassland. Favours closely cropped grassland kept short by frequent fires and intensive grazing.

fields.name: Poicephalus robustus
fields.notes: Breeds in Afromontane forests above 1000 m (Skead 1964; Wirminghaus 1999). Occurs at altitudes of 100-2000 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Gyps coprotheres
fields.notes: Forages over open grassland and woodland and is dependent on tall cliffs for breeding. Altitude: <2300 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Sterna balaenarum
fields.notes: It breeds mostly in extensive barren gravel plains in central and northern Namibia, on dry saltpans in gravel plains in southern Namibia and the Northern Cape, and in the unvegetated gravel slacks between dunes in the Western Cape and Eastern Cape.

fields.name: Tyto capensis
fields.notes: The Grass Owl is found almost exclusively in rank grass, typically, although not only, at fairly high altitudes (Cyrus & Robson 1980; Earle & Grobler 1987; Tarboton et al. 1987). It is secretive and nomadic. It has been recorded breeding in permanent and seasonal vleis, which it vacates while hunting or post-breeding (Tarboton et al. 1987), although it will breed in any area of long grass and is not necessarily associated with wetlands (W.R. Tarboton in litt.). When it does occur in marshes and vleis it is usually outnumbered by the Marsh Owl Asio capensis 10:1 (Tarboton et al. 1987). Elevation: <2100 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Phoenicopterus ruber
fields.notes: Core range is the central areas of the country where its occurrence matches the distribution of endorheic pans (Allan et al. 1995). Frequently recorded at estuaries and other wetlands along the west coast (ASAB1: 112-113).

fields.name: Balearica regulorum
fields.notes: Restricted to the moist, higher-rainfall, eastern portions of the region and is abundant at higher altitudes. Altitude: <2000 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Thalassarche chrysostoma
fields.notes: Breeds in colonies on vegetated cliffs close tot he coast at two localities on marion and Prince Edward Islands.

fields.name: Alcedo semitorquata
fields.notes: Afrotropical regions. Fast flowing rivers fringed with riparian vegetation. High rainfall areas in the east and extreme south.

fields.name: Phoenicopterus minor
fields.notes: Occurs on shallow saline and alkaline wetlands, such as saltpans and coastal lagoons (Brown et al. 1982; ASB1: 114-115).

fields.name: Falco naumanni
fields.notes: The preferred habitat is semi-arid grasslands, and particularly grassy Karoo, sweet and mixed grassveld and the central Kalahari vegetation types (ASAB1: 268-269). They avoid wooded areas but forage in agricultural lands, with small populatioons occurring in the wheat fields of the Western Cape, which have been derived from Fynbos and Renosterveld (Pepler 1996). Altitude 100-1800 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Polemaetus bellicosus
fields.notes: Naturally absent from the high mountains of Lesotho, heavily forested areas, and treeless landscapes.

fields.name: Heteromirafra ruddi
fields.notes: Highly selective and specialized. High-altitude (1700-2200 m.a.s.l.), open, moderately to heavily grazed, level grassland without forb invasion in high-rainfall (>600mm p.a) sour grassland regions (Dean et al. 1992). Prefers hill tops or plateau where it is almost restricted to Highland Sourveld to Cymbopogon-Themeda veld transition (Acocks veld type 56) and Northeastern Sandy Highveld (Acocks veld type 57) (Acocks 1975). Favours trampled areas with low ground cover (vegetation height <0.6m) where the cover of Eragrostis curvuls/E. chloromelas is high relative to that of Themeda triandra (Hockey et al 1988a). Avoids very dense tall stands of grass which develop in areas of low abundance and minimal grazing; occasionally inhabits dense sour grassveld 30-50cm high (Herholdt & Grobler 1987). Relatively high abundances are found at the most intensely grazed sites, suggesting that intensive grazing does not necessarily affect the species adversesly, providing such grazing does not lead to an invasion of forbs or other non-grasses (Hockey et al 1988a). Also favours edges of pans and vleis. Restricted to particular landscapes at particular altitudes which are naturally fragmented and highly localised, both spatially and temporally.

fields.name: Ephippiorhynchus senegalensis
fields.notes: Saddlebilled Storks occur in aquatic habitats in open country, favouring large rivers, freshwater wetlands and floodplains (Hancock et al. 1992). Large trees are required for roosting and nesting. Elevation: <1000 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Zoothera guttata
fields.notes: In summer it breeds in large (>100 ha) patches of mature coastal forest (Eastern Cape) or coastal scarp and valley forests (KwaZulu-Natal) with a closed canopy and a relatively open lower strata (Harebottle 1994). A large proportion of the southern breeding populations undertake a littoral migration northwards and spend the nonbreeding season in central coastal KwaZulu-Natal, where they are found in mature coastal and lowland forest, coastal scarp forest, dune forest, secondary growth and occasionally in suburban gardens. The latter are used mainly as stop-over points on migration. There is also evidence of altitudinal migration in the northern KwaZulu-Natal breeding populations, with some birds spending the winter at coastal forests along the KwaZulu-Natal north coast (H. Chittenden in litt). Elevation: <600 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Gorsachius leuconotus
fields.notes: It occurs singly and in pairs along swift- and slow-flowing rivers and streams with heavily wooded margins or overhanging vegetation. It occasionally utilises small dams with dense overhanging vegetation. Forages along the margins of waterways by night and roosts within dense vegetation during the day. Some seasonal movements are possible, but it appears to be mostly sedentary throughout the year. Altitude: <1500 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Sarothrura ayresi
fields.notes: Apparently restricted to a few high-altitude marshes, with a small population and highly specific habitat requirements. They may also occur, at least occasionally, at smaller patches of suitable marshy habitat within the known range.

fields.name: Gyps africanus
fields.notes: Its distribution correlates with drier woodlands and tall trees such as Acacia spp., Fius spp. and Adansonia digitata, which it uses for roosting and breeding. Altitude: <1500 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Aquila rapax
fields.notes: Woodlands, including lightly wooded areas. Altitude: <1600 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Ardeotis kori
fields.notes: Semi arid regions of South Africa within the 100-600mm rainfall isohyets (ASAB1: 346-347). it is a bird of dry savannas, but is widespead in moise and semi-arid woodlands. Altitude: 100-1600 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Ciconia nigra
fields.notes: Montane breeding habitat is not under threat. Reliant on shallow waterbodies.

fields.name: Circaetus fasciolatus
fields.notes: Lowland evergreen forest but will exploit stands of alien trees in its range. Altitude: <200 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Eupodotis caerulescens
fields.notes: Grassland Karoo. Regularly forages in crop fields and planted pastures.

fields.name: Geronticus calvus
fields.notes: High-rainfall (>700mm p.a.) sour and alpine grassland, characterised by an absence of trees and a short, dense grass sward (Manry 1985).

fields.name: Neotis ludwigii
fields.notes: Range is centred on the Nama Karoo and Succulent Karoo biomes (ASAB1: 350-351).

fields.name: Terathopius ecaudatus
fields.notes: Found throughout the non-forested habitats of sub-Saharan Africa (Brown et al. 1982). It occurs in a wide variety of woodland types, from open, semi-arid Kalahari to well-developed, ratively mesic broadleaved woodland. Altitude: <800 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Neotis denhami
fields.notes: Grassland and open light woodland. Altitude: <2000 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Euphorbia Aiton subsp. meloformis forma falsa
Euphorbia R.A.Dyer
fields.notes: Occurs in habitats <1500m above sea level (altitude). Avoids both stagnant water and fast-flowing waters, referring clear, perennial rivers and streams lined with reeds and overhanging trees and shrubs (Barnes, 2000).

fields.name: Euphorbia Aiton subsp. meloformis forma meloformis
Euphorbia Aiton subsp. meloformis forma magna
Caprimulgus natalensis
fields.notes: Restricted to the littoral coastal plain of northern KwaZulu-Natal, from Mtunzini to Kosi Bay (ASAB1: 608-609).

fields.name: Halcyon senegaloides
fields.notes: Mangroves, estuaries and associated coastal riverine vegetation. Usually within 20 km of ht ecoast (Fry et al. 1988; ASAB1: 652-653). Altitude: <100 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Calendulauda burra
fields.notes: Favours Eragrostis ciliate and S. brevifolia grasses. Altitude: 600-1100 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Stactolaema olivacea
fields.notes: The barbet is primarily dependent on the fruit of wild figs Ficus spp., seven species of which occur in Ongoye Forest and another two in surrounding bush clumps (Johnson et al., 1998; Chittenden et al., 1999). Altitude: 300-500 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Bradypterus sylvaticus
fields.notes: Restricted to higher fragmented forest patches in coastal regions of the Eastern Cape and Western Cape, South Africa. Typically occurs in thick tangled vegetation along the banks of watercourses, or covering drainage lines in forest patches in the fynbos biome or on the edges of Afromontane forest. The species occurs in the lowest 1-2 m of vegetation, and apparently spends much time foraging on the ground. Altitude <1000 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Anthus brachyurus
fields.notes: Highly localised and scarce altitudinal migrant or resident in high-rainfall sour grassland. Shorttailed Pipit has a highly specific habitat requirement and it is known to inhabit short open grassland, less than 15 cm high, sometimes scattered with trees and shrubs, in flat or slightly hilly ground, usually moist with sometimes recently burnt (Lawson 1980). Altitude: <1850 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Anthus chloris
fields.notes: Breeds in submontane undulating grasslands, generally at high altitudes. During breeding it favours lush, long grass and daisyfield conditions, where it frequents areas of tussock and grassy slopes in mountainous country (Clancey 1985b). It is restricted to a narrow range of altitudes (e.g. 2000-2300 m a.s.l around Wakkerstroom) and a specific set of ecological requirements (e.g. flat of gently sloping ground). Altitude: 1400-2400 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Buphagus africanus
fields.notes: Primary hosts, Buffalo Syncerus caffer and antelope, with the ticks Amblyomma habraeum and Rhipicephalus appendiculatus are an essential requirement. Altitude: <1900 m a.s.l.

fields.name: Phoebetria palpebrata
fields.notes: Frequents colder waters mainly south of the Antarctic Polar Front, especially during the austral summer (Marchant & Higgins 1990; del Hoyo et al. 1992).

fields.name: Macronectes giganteus
fields.notes: Breeding range extends from 40S to 67S on southern cool-temperate, subantarctic and Antarctic islands, Antarctica and South America (Argentina and Chile). The extensive pelagic range stretches from the Antarctic pack-ice to subtropical waters at c. 20S (Marchant & Higgins 1990).

fields.name: Macronectes halli
fields.notes: Breeds on subantarctic islands located to the north of the antarctic Polar Front in the south Atlantic, Indian and southwest Pacific oceans (Marchant & Higgins 1990; Patterson et al. in press). Circumpolar pelagic distribution, typically from 30S-64S (Marchant & Higgins 1990).

fields.name: Phalacrocorax capensis
fields.notes: Breeds at 69 localities between Die Oase (19 27'S, 12 42'E) and Stag Island (33 50S, 26 17'E), although less than 2% of the population breeds east of Cape Agulhas (20E).

fields.name: Circus maurus
fields.notes: Heavily concentrated in the wheat and pasture lands and fynbos areas of the Western Cape (Chadwick 1997), succulent Karroo in Namaqualand and grassveld and Nama Karoo of the Eastern Cape, Lesotho and Free State (ASAB1: 241-243).

fields.name: Lissotis melanogaster
fields.notes: Grassland and savanna of sub-Saharan Africa. In South Africa it is found largely east of the great escarpment, where it inhabits open grassland and densely wooded savanna.

fields.name: Vanellus melanopterus
fields.notes: The species tends to prefer short and/or burnt grassland; it undertakes local attitudinal movements in parts of the range and it may be nomadic (Underhill et al. 1999b).

fields.name: Vanellus albiceps
fields.notes: The species frequents sandbars and more open, denuded sections of riverbanks. Kemp (1980) found that it no longer nests at former breeding sites along the Limpopo River west of the Kruger National Park.

fields.name: Glareola pratincola
fields.notes: In Swaziland the speices only breeds and forages in sugarcane fields (Parker 1994b).

fields.name: Glareola nordmanni
fields.notes: This species is greatly attracted to agricultural landscapes within the grassland biome, particularly intensively cultivated areas under-going regular ploughing and harvesting (W.R. Tarboton in litt.)

fields.name: Sterna caspia
fields.notes: All along the coastline but mostly at estuaries; in the interior most recores are from the highveld.

fields.name: Pterocles gutturalis
fields.notes: The species inhabits short open grassveld, fallow fields and recently burnt veld on black clay soils; coarser soils derived from quartzite, granite or felsite are avoided (Tarboton et al. 1999). In South Africa it tends to avoid natural, pristine Acacia savanna, preferring agricultural fields - particularly one-year fallow fields and recently harvested or ploughed fields (Tarboton et al. 1999).

fields.name: Centropus grillii
fields.notes: Tall, dense moist grassland, associated with the fringes of wetlands.

fields.name: Campethera notata
fields.notes: Forested belt of the coastal plain, ranging marginally inland in places (ASAB1: 742-743).

fields.name: Certhilauda chuana
fields.notes: Open habitat, sparsely vegetated with short grass and scattered trees or bushes, particularly where the grass has been severely grazed (Dean et al. 1992). In South Africa it is associated with Tarchonanthus savanna (Brooke 1984a).

fields.name: Schoenicola brevirostris
fields.notes: It is localised to patchy habitat: tall, dense, rank grassland typically in moist areas.

fields.name: Macronyx ameliae
fields.notes: Endemic to the Afrotropics, with several disjunct populations in southern, Central and East Africa (Keith et al. 1992).

fields.name: Spermestes fringilloides
fields.notes: Except for KwaZulu-Natal, it is often linked elsewhere to Oxytenanthera abyssinica, a favoured food plant (Irvin 1981). The Pied Mannikin's rarity is something of a mystery for it does not appear to be a habitat specialist. Typical habitat is thick damp growth, with seeding grasses, on forest fringes, with or without alien weeds, often adjacent to canefields, gardens and other human modified terrain.

fields.name: Crithagra citrinipectus
fields.notes: Closely associated with lala palms Hyphaene coriacea, especially for nesting.

fields.name: Morus capensis
fields.notes: Breeds on six islands in the world: Lambert's Bay, Malgas, Bird, Mercury, Ichaboe and Possession island. Altitude: sea level.

fields.name: Phalacrocorax neglectus
fields.notes: A strictly marine species, it breeds on rocks, walls or artificial platforms in close proximity to ht esea (Cooper 1981). Altitude: sea level.

fields.name: Sterna virgata
fields.notes: Appear never to venture beyond the inshore regions of their breeding islands (Weimerskirch & Stahl 1988). They feed within two kilometres from land, over open seas and kelp beds, but most feeding is over the surf zone along the shore and in intertidal rock pools (Berruti & Harris 1976; Weimerskirch & Stahl 1988; Sagar 1991). Altitude: Sea level.

fields.name: Phalacrocorax melanogenis
fields.notes: Subantarctic Prince Edward Islands and Marion Island

fields.morphology: Robust pelagiid reaching up to 80 cm in diameter as medusa. Adults with 24, thread-like tentacles (3 per octant); 8 of which (1 per octant) persistent on capture; 32 approximately quadrangular marginal lappets (4 per octant); with gastrovascular canals. Quadralinga absent. Oral arms voluminously spiraled proximally. The species is defined by thread-like nature of marginal tentacles, lappets with canals and form of the oral arms. Colours vary with age; juveniles rose pink, without bell markings, but with maroon tentacles; adults with rose pink base to bell, red/brown compass marks, maroon tentacles and orange/brown oral arms.
fields.trophic: Feeds on zooplankton and benthic micro-crustaceans. Hosts often significant numbers of parasitic hyperiid amphipods.
fields.uses: None at present, caught as by-catch of commercial fisheries.
fields.distribution: Angola to Western Agulhas Bank
fields.reproduction: Sexes of medusae separate, apparently releasing gametes in the water. The polyp (known from laboratory cultures) produces new polyps mostly by stolon budding, but can also proliferate by direct budding, splitting and podocyst formation; medusae are released by polydisc strobilation following a drop in water temperature below 14 Celcius.
fields.movement: All size classes present throughout the year off Namibia, suggesting that the life span is greater than 12 months. Populations off Namibia Â attain greatest numbers during winter and spring. Larger individuals tend to be found more commonly further offshore than smaller ones, and slightly deeper, though present throughout the water column.Â Less common off South Africa, where it is most abundant during summer and autumn.

fields.morphology: Dorado have iridescent blue greenhead and body that fades to golden below with numerous spots. The dorsal fin is dark blue with pale spots. Juveniles have about 15 dark bars that extend into the dorsal and anal fins. Body depth is greatest behind the head tapering towards the tail. The anal fin margin of adults is concave on the front half of fin and they have long pectoral fins that are more than half the head length. There is an oval patch of villiform teeth on the tongue.Â
fields.trophic: Adults normally feed on small fish, especially pelagic drifters such as juvenile trigger fish but also take crustaceans, nautilus, squid and a wide variety of planktonic organisms (Bannister 1976, van der Elst 1993, Oxenford and Hunte 1999, Tripp-Valdez et al. 2010, Collette et al. 2011). They also feed on flying fish, mackerel and small carangids (Heemstra and Heemstra 2004). Juvenile dorado eat planktonic organisms such as fish and crustacean larvae (van der Elst 1993).
fields.uses: Highly prized commercial and recreational species throughout its circumglobal range (Collette et al. 2011) but are seldom specifically targeted by commercial skiboat fishers in South Africa but does Â forms a major component of the recreational skiboat sector (Dunlop and Mann 2013). Occasionally caught in the recreational boat sector in the EC (Brouwer and Buxton 2002) and forms a small percentage of the catch in the SA spearfishery (Mann et al. 1997b). Caught as a bycatch in the pelagic longline fisheries in the SW Indian Ocean (Adrill et al. 2011).
fields.distribution: Distributed throughout SA waters to 35Â° south with occasional large adults being caught off the Cape south coast (Smith and Heemstra 1991, van der Elst 1993).Â
fields.reproduction: Dorado are gonochoristic, multiple spawners that show sexual dimorphism with males growing larger and having a steeper forehead (Oxenford and Hunte 1986a). Spawning usually takes place in summer, although it has been recorded throughout the year (Shcherbachev 1973, Oxenford and Hunte 1986a, b, van der Elst 1993, Ditty et al. 1994, Massuti and Morales-Nin 1997, Benjamin and Kurup 2012, McBride et al. 2012).Spawning takes place in tropical oceanic waters, often closer to shore (Shcherbachev 1973, Ditty et al. 1994, Massuti and Morales-Nin 1995, 1997, Benjamin and Kurup 2012, McBride et al. 2012).Age at maturity varies considerably between different regions but is from 3 to 5 months off Florida and Barbados (Oxenford and Hunte 1986a, Collette et al. 2011, McBride et al. 2012).Size at maturity also varies but is around 65-70cm FL for females and 75-80cm FL for males (Oxenford and Hunte 1986a, b, Massuti and Morales-Nin 1997, Heemstra and Heemstra 2004, McBride et al. 2012).
fields.movement: Dorado are largely nomadic although some pre-spawning migration has been proposed in the western and tropical areas of the Atlantic Ocean (Oxenford and Hunte 1986a, b, Massuti and Morales-Nin 1995, Collette et al. 2011).

fields.morphology: Bank steenbras have a pale grey body with darker heads and fins and usually a red stripe in front of the eye. The pectoral fins have six characteristic enlarged rays. Their length is 2.7-2.9 times the body depth and the dorsal fin has 17-18 spines and 22-24 rays.
fields.trophic: Adult bank steenbras feed on small bottom dwelling invertebrates, squid and small fish (Smith and Bauchot 1984, Meyer and Smale 1991). The diet of juveniles is assumed to be similar to adults (Smith and Bauchot 1984).
fields.uses: Caught as a bycatch of the inshore trawl fishery and boat-based linefisheries, although seldom takes bait. Much sought after target species by spearfishermen (Smith and Bauchot 1984, Smith and Heemstra 1991).
fields.distribution: Walvis Bay possibly to Port St John but mostly in deeper water off Eastern Cape and Western Cape (Heemstra and Heemstra 2004). KZN records probably confused with C. jessicalenorum (Smith and Heemstra 1991).

fields.morphology: Blue stingrays have a rhomboidal shaped disk which is naked except for some denticles near the front margin. The nose is angular abs the ventral finfold of the tail falls well short of tail tip. They are a golden brown colour dorsally with irregular blue marking, the underside is white.Â
fields.trophic: The diet of the blue sting ray varies with size foraging zone. When feeding in the surf zone prey items include Callianassa spp., Donax spp. and polychaetes but beyond the backline the main prey are Balanoglossus capensis and Callianassa spp. (EbertÂ and Cowley 2003). It is not known what the diet of juveniles consists of.Â
fields.uses: Popular target species for recreational shore anglers, especially during shore angling competitions (Cowley 1990, 1997, Radervand and Govender 2003). Occasionally taken by both recreational and commercial skiboat fishers but are normally discarded. Juveniles are caught offshore as a bycatch by inshore trawlers in the SE and SW Cape. Adults sometimes caught as a bycatch in beach seines in False Bay (P. Cowley, SAIAB, pers. obs.) and off Durban beach (B. Mann, ORI, pers. obs.).
fields.distribution: A single stock is assumed to occur from Angola to northern KZN (P. Cowley, SAIAB, pers. obs.).
fields.reproduction: Blue rays are viviparous with 1 to seven pups been born after a nine months gestation period (Cowley 1990, Ebert and Cowley 2009). Pups are then born in early summer from October to November (Cowley 1990) in sheltered bays and estuary mouths in the Eastern and western Cape (Cowley 1990) the juveniles then move offshore for their first one to two years (Cowley 1990).Â Males reach maturity at 5 years and females at 7 years (Cowley 1990) when they reach a length of 395mm DW and 505mm respectively (Ebert and Cowley 2009).
fields.movement: Little is known of the movements of the blue stingray as very few have been recaptured off South Africa (ORI Tagging Project unpubl. Data). They are found inshore in summer and then move further offshore during winter which is related to reproductive seasonality (Buxton et al. 1984, Cowley 1988, 1990).Â

fields.morphology: Natal fingerfin have a reddish head and body that is darker dorsally and fades to white below. The dorsal scales at the front of the body have a dark spot at the centre and there is a dark red or black blotch on the flap of skin at the upper pectoral base. The pectoral fin has 14 rays with the lower 6 characteristically lengthened. The total length is 2.6 to 2.8 times the body depth and the dorsal fin has 17-18 spines and 26-27 rays.Â
fields.trophic: Adults are day time predators which feed on small, benthic invertebrates, but also squid and small fish (van der Elst 1993,Â Heemstra and Heemstra 2004). The diet of juveniles is unknown but small juveniles are thought to feed on zooplankton.
fields.uses: Â Taken mainly by spearfishers (van der Elst 1993) but forms only a small component of their catches (Mann et al. 1997a, Lloyd et al. 2012).
fields.distribution: Found from Algoa Bay in the eastern Cape north to Sodwana Bay, Kwa-Zulu Natal (van der Elst 1993, Heemstra and Heemstra 2004).
fields.reproduction: Little is known about the reproductive strategy of Natal fingerfin. Spawning strategy and season is not known although eggs are most commonly found in winter. Exact spawning location is not known but eggs have been collected along the 20 to 30m depth contour off Park Rynie on the KZN south coast each year between 1987 and 2011 (Connell 2012).
fields.movement: Natal fingerfin are known to congregate at certain times of the year into loosely packed shoals which are thought to be to spawn (van der Elst 1993).

fields.morphology: Santer are silvery pink with 4 or 5 faint red bars that are much darker in juveniles and a faint dark bar through their eye. Their body depth is greater that their head length. The dorsal has 11-12 spines and the first two spines are short with a characteristically elongated 3rd to 7th spine, especially in juveniles.Â
fields.trophic: Adults are piscivores that feed on species such as pilchards and small reef fishes but also squid, octopus and crabs (Coetzee and Baird 1981b, Garratt 1986, Smale 1986). Juvenile Santer feed on mysids, penaeids, octopus and small reef fish such as gobies (Coetzee and Baird1981b, Garratt 1986, Smale 1986)
fields.uses: Santer are caught in the commercial and recreational skiboat fishery (Garratt 1985a, Smale and Buxton 1985, van der Elst 1989, Penney et al. 1989, Timochin 1992, Mann et al. 1997a, Brouwer and Buxton 2002, Fennessy et al. 2003, Dunlop and Mann 2013) although they are seldom taken by spearfishermen (van der Elst 1993). Also recorded infrequently from inshore bottom trawls along the southern Cape coast (Attwood et al. 2011), and offÂ Mozambique and in the Gulf of Aden (Druzhnin 1975, Piotrovski 1990, Timochin 1992).
fields.distribution: From Mozambique to Cape Agulhas in the Western Cape (Garratt 1985a, b, Smale 1986).
fields.reproduction: Santer are rudimentary hermaphrodites and functional gonochorists (Coetzee 1983, Garratt 1985b, Buxton and Garratt 1990, Garratt 1991) but spawning behavior and early gonadal development suggest the possibility of protogynous sex change (Garratt 1993). Santer spawn throughout their distribution ranges, in Mozambique spawning takes place from June to October with a peak in July and August (Piotrovski 1990). In Kwa-Zulu Natal spawning is from May to November peaking between August and October (Garratt 1985b, Garratt 1991). In the Eastern Cape Santer spawn from November to February peaking between Â December and January (Coetzee 1983). Santer reach maturity at 3-4 years (Coetzee and Baird 1981b) when they are 250mm FL (females, KZN Garratt 1985b) 340mm TL (eastern Cape, Coetzee 1983) and 258mm FL (Mozambique, Torres 2009). Eggs are pelagic and are distributed inshore of the Agulhas Current (Garratt 1985b).
fields.movement: Santer are nomadic species that are well known to undertake local movements into shallow water during stormy weather or following cold water upwelling events (Smith and Heemstra 1991). Although they do not undertake extensive migrations, santer do move up to 10 km between reef complexes (Wilke and Griffiths 1990, Griffiths and Wilke 2002).

fields.morphology: Dusky sharks are large sharks with broadly rounded snouts and curved moderate-sized pectoral fins. They have an interdorsal ridge and have triangular saw-edged upper teeth. They are blue-grey to lead-grey above with white below. The tips of pectoral and pelvic fins, as well as lower lobe of caudal fin and dorsal fins often dusky in young but plain in adults.
fields.trophic: Dusky sharks are apex predators that will feed on a variety of prey including teleosts, elasmobranchs and cephalopods. Small sharks preferÂ  small pelagic teleosts and squid(Smale 1991, Stevens 1990, Simpfendorfer pers. data) and as they grow prey size also increases with larger teleosts and elasmobranchsÂ  become more important in the diet (Bass et al. 1973, van der Elst 1979, Castro 1983, Smale 1991, Gelshleichter et al. 1998)
fields.uses: Neonates and juveniles are exploited in KZN and EC waters by recreational and commercial linefisheries, and juvenile, adolescent and adult dusky sharks are captured in the protective shark nets in KZN (Dudley 2004, Dudley et al. 2005, Govender and Birnie 1997, Pradervand 2004, Pradervand 2007). Dusky sharks are also taken as bycatch in the offshore pelagic longline fishery (Petersen et al. 2009).
fields.distribution: Eastern seaboard of SA (Compagno et al. 1989).
fields.reproduction: The Dusky shark is placentally viviparous (Bass et al. 1973, Wourms 1981) and litters have anywhere from 3 to 16 pups (Last and Stevens 1994, Dudley et al. 2005).They have a prolonged breeding season from Â February to December with a peak from March to July (Dudley et al. 2005). Pups are born at around 61-70cm PCL but may exceed 70cm (Dudley et al. 2005). Mating and most of the gestation period occurs away from KZN nearshore waters (Bass et al. 1973, Dudley et al. 2005). Pupping occurs in nearshore waters between Richards Bay and the KZN/EC border but the northern part of that region, adjacent to the Thukela Bank, may be preferred (Dudley et al. 2005). Male dusky sharks reach maturity at 16.7-19.7 and females at 17.5-20.6 years at a length of 211cm PCL and Â 215cm PCL respectively (Dudley and Simpfendorfer 2006).
fields.movement: Small dusky sharks are known to migrate southwards from central/southern KZN to the Eastern and Southern Cape but do not appear to remain in Cape waters in winter (Hussey et al. 2009). It is not clear whether all young sharks undertake this migration though. Large sharks move inshore seasonally from the outer shelf (Bass et al. 1973).

fields.morphology: Ragged toothed sharks have a short, pointed snout, small eyes, and small, equal-sized dorsal and anal fins. The 1st dorsal fin is closer to the pelvic fin than to the pectoral fins.The caudal fin has a pronounced subterminal notch and a short ventral lobe. There is a pale brown or grey colour that is paler below. They also have dark spots that are unique to each individual which appear faded in adults. These spots are absent from the fins. They have characteristic protruding spike-like teeth which gives them their common name.
fields.trophic: Ragged toothed sharks are opportunistic ambush predators that will also co-operatively by forming packs to concentrate prey (Ireland 1984, Smale 2005). Adults and juveniles both will eat a variety of teleost fish as well as smaller elasmobranchs and will also eat invertebrates such as squid, crabs and lobsters (Bass et al. 1975, Compagno 2001, Smale 2005) and are considered to be ambush predators.Â
fields.uses: Although protected from commercial fishing in SA since 1998, bycatch in any fishery potentially poses a threat to ragged toothed sharks. They are rarely caught commercially due to their inshore habitat preferences but it is vulnerable to recreational shore anglers, recreational and commercial skiboat anglers although most catches by shore anglers are released alive. Protective legislation in the form of decommercialisation was specifically introduced to prevent its capture and sale (especially of the fins) by boat anglers. Adults are caught in fairly large numbers (168 per annum Â±105 s.d., 1978-2010) in shark nets in KZN during their reproductive migrations (Dudley and Simpfendorfer 2006).
fields.distribution: In SA ragged toothed sharks have occasionally been reported from the west coast, but are more commonly found along the east coast from Cape Town to northern KZN (Bass et al. 1975; Smale 2002; Dicken et al. 2006, 2007 and 2008).
fields.reproduction: Ragged toothed sharks are ovoviviparous and aplacental species, with the developing embryos obtaining nutrition through both oophagy and uterine cannibalism (Bass et al. 1975, GrantÂ et al. 1983, Gilmore 1993, Branstetter and Musick 1994). Only two pups survive per litter due to this cannibalistic behavior, and gestation is 9-12 months (Bass et al. 1975, GrantÂ et al. 1983). At birth pups are between 95 and 120cm in length (Cadenat 1956, Taniuchi 1970, Bass et al. 1975). In Australia ragged toothed sharks are through to reproduce annually (Gilmore 1993, Gordon 1993) however in South Africa it they are thought to follow a two year cycle, with a 12-15 month resting stage between pregnancies (G. Cliff, KZNSB, unpubl. data, Dicken et al. 2006, 2007).Ragged toothed shark mate from October to November (Dicken et al. 2006). Pregnant females then migrate northward to spend the first part of their gestation in the warmer waters of northern KZN and possibly southern MOZ. Starting in June pregnant females then move southwards towards the cooler waters in the Eastern Cape to pup (Wallett 1973, Bass et al. 1975, Dicken et al. 2006, 2007). Here they pup between September and Nov (Smale 2002, Dicken et al. 2006). Young sharks remain in the eastern cape nursery areas until they are first 4â5 years, and then join the subadult and adult components of the population (Dicken et al. 2006, 2007). Male ragged toothed sharks reach maturity atÂ  6-7 years and females at 9-10 years (Western North Atlantic, Goldman et al. 2006) when they are 162.9cm PCL and 175.4cm PCL respectively (Dudley and Simpfendorfer 2006).
fields.movement: Mature female ragged toothed sharks undergo a biennial migration along the east coast to mate (Bass et al. 1975, Smale 2002, Dicken et al. 2006, 2007). See Reproduction for more details.

fields.morphology: Great white sharks have a robust fusiform body that is dark blueing grey or bronzy above with a sharp transition to white underside. They have a blunt conical snout that is shorter than their mouth width. The origin of the first dorsal fin is in front of the pectoral inner corner. The pectoral fins are often dusky or black and there is often a black spot at the axil of the pectoral fins.Â
fields.trophic: Adult wide sharks are active predators that have a highly varied diet, marine mammals (cetaceans and seals), bony and cartilaginous fish and cephalopods make up the bulk of their prey (Bass et al. 1975, Cliff et al. 1989, 1996a). They are also opportunistic scavengers that will commonly feed off whale carcasses (Dicken 2008). Juvenilesâ diet is similar to adults (Bass et al. 1975, Cliff et al. 1989, 1996b).Â
fields.uses: Prior to full protection of this species in 1991 (Compagno 1991), trophy hunting for extremely large individuals in the SW CapeÂ was a major source of mortality. Currently approximately 30 individuals, almost all of which are immature, are caught annually in the KZN shark nets. Increased targeting of juveniles by shore anglers in the SW Cape has been reported recently; the animals are generally returned alive, but mortalities through capture stress are unknown.
fields.distribution: This species occurs along the entire South African coast but its regional distribution is centered in the South Western Cape (Bass et al. 1975).
fields.habitat_narrative: HABITATJuveniles: Similar to adults (Compagno 2001).
fields.reproduction: Great white sharks are ovoviviparous and embryos practice uterine cannibalism in the form of oophagy, as they eat unfertilized eggs (Gilmore 1993, Francis 1996).Very little is known on spawning and breading of this species however the capture of a 140cm TL (20 kg) individual (Smith 1951) and sighting of small individuals (approx. 150cm TL) in Algoa Bay (Dicken 2008)Â suggests that the Eastern Cape, and specifically Algoa Bay, may represent a nursery ground for this species. Small individuals (153-157cm TL) have also been caught in the KZN shark nets (Dudley 2012).Males reach maturity at 8-9 years and females at only around 16 years (Dudley 2012) when they are 309cm PCL (Dudley and Simpfendorfer 2006) and 396cm (Dudley 2012) respectively.Â
fields.movement: White sharks are nomadic and in South Africa have shown a number of different movement types. They have been known to undertake trans-oceanic return migrations (Western Australia), as well as making frequent long-distance coastal return migrations, smaller-scale patrolling and site fidelity (Bonfil et al. 2005). Great whites may also show site fidelity or repeated use of migratory routes (Cliff et al. 1996b).

fields.morphology: The blacktip shark is a stout shark with a long, narrow, pointed snout, long gill slits, a high first dorsal fin and no interdorsal ridge. Â Dark grey, ashy blue or dusky bronze on back, belly white or yellowish white; a dark band extending rearward along each side to about over origin of pelvic fin; tips of pelvic fins with a persistent black spot; tips of dorsal fins, pectoral fins, anal, and lower lobe of caudal fin usually black or dusky in young individuals, fading with growth.Â
fields.trophic: Adult blacktip sharks are predators which the bulk of the diet made up of teleosts (Dudley and Cliff 1993). Important prey species include Trachurus delagoa and Sardinops sagax (Dudley and Cliff 1993, 2010).
fields.uses: Caught by recreational shore and boat anglers. Ranked third (in terms of numbers) in the shark catch of competition anglers in KZN and northern EC (Pradervand 2004, Pradervand et al. 2007). A mean annual catch of 97 sharks was taken in the protective gill-nets (shark nets) off KZN beaches between 1978 and 2010 (KZNSB unpubl. data).
fields.distribution: Cape Point northwards (Compagno 1984, Compagno et al. 1989).
fields.habitat_narrative: Adults are pelagic but not truly oceanic (Compagno 1984). On KZN coast, penetrates the surf zone and occasionally St Lucia Estuary; offshore, seldom caught in water >30m (Bass et al. 1975).Young animals may use coastal waters of Mozambique (Bass et al. 1975) but this is not certain, elsewhere, they are known to use coastal waters, including estuarine salt marshes and tidal creeks, as a nursery (Branstetter and McEachran 1987, Castro 1993).
fields.reproduction: Blacktip sharks reproductive strategy is placental viviparity (Branstetter 1981) and gestation period is about 12 months (Dudley and Cliff 1993). Mating takes place from November to December and is thought to occur outside of KZN (Dudley and Cliff 1993). Similarly, pregnant females appear to move elsewhere to pup, possibly the coastal waters of Mozambique (Bass et al.1975). Male blacktip sharks reach maturity at 5.7 years and females at 6.1 yearsÂ  (Wintner and Cliff 1996) and at a length of 147.7cm PCL and 151.7cm PCL respectively (Dudley and Simpfendorfer 2006).
fields.movement: Blacktip sharks are present in KZN all year but less abundant from July to October. They are thought to undergo a breeding migration and may display different migratory behavior between sexes (Dudley and Cliff 1993). There is a suggestion of sit fidelity in blacktip sharks (KZNSB unpubl. data). Evidence for philopatry for nursery areas among female blacktip sharks on the US Atlantic coast is presented by Keeney et al. (2003).

fields.morphology: Zambezi sharks have a broadly rounded short snout that is about half a mouth width in length. The origin of the first dorsal fin is over the inner edge of the pectoral and the second dorsal origin is over the front of the anal fin origin. The first dorsal is double the height of the second. There is no interdorsal ridge in the species and it has a robust body. Juveniles have a dusky tip to their fins and adults have a plain colour.Â
fields.trophic: Adults are active predators which will take any prey, with increasing size, Zambezi sharks will take more elasmobranches. Sea turtles, marine and terrestrial mammals, birds, crustaceans and cephalopods are occasionally taken (Bass et al 1973, Cliff and Dudley 1991). Smaller juvenile Zambezi sharks in rivers and lakes prey on a high proportion of teleosts while smaller sharks are taken in rivers and lakes (Bass et al 1973). Sea turtles, mammals and invertebrates are occasionally taken (Cliff and Dudley 1991).
fields.uses: Important in the competitive shore fishery, primarily in KZN but extending into the EC; but most specimens are released. Also caught year-round in the bather protection nets of the KZNSB but mainly in summer (Cliff and Dudley 1991). Some recreational ski-boat anglers target this species around Protea Banks in southern KZN.
fields.distribution: Western Cape to Mozambique, Recently described as occurring in the Breede.
fields.habitat_narrative: Adults Zambezi sharks are found in coastal waters including inshore and offshore reefs, the surf zone, estuaries, rivers (Heemstra and Heemstra 2004).Juveniles, especially new borns appear to be confined to their nursery areas in coastal lagoons, turbid estuaries and rivers (Bass et al 1973; Heemstra and Heemstra 2004).
fields.reproduction: Zambezi sharks are viviparous, with yolk-sac placenta (Compagno et al. 2005). In South Africa a prolonged mating and pupping season is possible (Cliff and Dudley 1991) as embryos of similar size were found on the KZN coast in both summer and winter. In Florida the gestation period is known to be 10-11 months (Clark and von Schmidt 1965) however data for South Africa is not available. Pupping season is thought to be between November and February (Bass et al 1973, Cliff and Dudley 1991).Zambezi sharks mate off northern KZN and spend the early stages of pregnancy here with the Â St Lucia Estuary being the only knownÂ nursery area on the KZN coast. Other large estuarine systems on the SA east coast, including Richards Bay (van der Elst 1993) and the Umzimvubu River and adjacent rivers (KZNSB, unpubl. data) may also act as nursery areas. Male and female Zambezi sharks reach maturity at 20 and 21 years respectively and when the males are 188 cm and the females 192cm PCL (Dudley and Simpfendorfer 2006).
fields.movement: Satellite telemetry studies suggest that Zambezi sharks are capable of long distance migrations (one individual was tracked form the Western Cape to Mozambique). Zambezi sharks are however generally thought to be seasonal residents in some areas, but the degree and extent of residency and migration are uncertain (McCord et al. in prep).

fields.morphology: The slinger is a deep bodied species with a very steep forehead and a noticeable bump above the eyes in older fish. The body is rosy coloured with iridescent blue spots and a distinct blue bar below the eye. Fins are translucent pink and the tail has an orange tinge and is moderately forked. The dorsal fin has 12 spines and ten rays, the anal fin has three spines and eight rays. The snout immediately above the mouth is naked. Slinger grows to around 60 cm but fish around 30 cm are more common.
fields.trophic: Adult slinger are opportunistic predators that mainly eat benthic crustaceans, molluscs and echinoderms (Garratt 1986) and juveniles feed on smaller benthic crustaceans including decapods,Â amphipods,Â copepods, and mysids as well as echinoderms including crinoids, ophiuroids and echinoids (Garratt 1985c, 1986).
fields.uses: The slinger is the most important species caught in the commercial linefishery in KwaZulu-Natal and, until recently, also in southern Mozambique (Garratt 1985a, Lichucha et al. 1999, Lichucha 2001, Mutombene 2013) and is also an important component in the recreational ski-boat fishery in KwaZulu-Natal and southern Mozambique (Mann et al. 1997, Penney et al. 1999, Fennessy et al. 2012, Dunlop and Mann 2013). This species is the principal food fish of KwaZulu-Natal, South Africa (Garratt1986).
fields.distribution: Eastern Cape
fields.reproduction: The slinger is a serial spawning protogynous hermaphrodite (Garratt 1985b,Garratt 1993). Females reach maturity at an average length of 24 cm FL and sex change occurs once they reach a size of 24 cm FL (Garratt 1985b, Lichucha 2001). Females are an average age of 3 years and change sex at 5 years of age (Garratt et al. 1993). The spawning season is extendedÂ  with peak spawning occurring from August to OctoberÂ  in Â KwaZulu-Natal (Garratt 1985b) with most spawning taking place in southern Mozambique and northern KwaZulu-Natal on offshore reefs (Garratt 1985b).
fields.movement: Slinger over four years of age show high residency only moving around 8 km (Mann 2013) with relative few having undertaken extensive migrations (Punt et al 1993a). Juvenile slinger younger than 4 years of age may migrate northwards from juvenile areas in southern Kwa-Zulu Natal and northern Transkei towards Mozambique (Buxton 1993b, Garratt 1993a, Maggs et al in press).Â
